[UTCTime "01:43:17"]

1. d4 { Attempting to help unerstand the idea of weak squares using Rubinstein V Lasker. I unfortunately did not note the date on this game, as they played many times. Maybe somebody will tell me one day. } 1... d5 2. c4 c6 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 g6 5. Nf3 Bg7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O { Looks pretty normal eh? } 7... Nbd7 { When black makes this move, white decides to create a plan based on weak squares. The more we understand this game, the better we can understand weak squares in general. } 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 cxd5 { With the pawns in symmetry - meaning each pawn across from a counterpart of the other color - and both missing a c pawn, the game play often shifts to the queen's side of the chess board. } 10. Qb3 { This is probably due to the simple reason that both sets of pieces naturally aim towards that side of the board. BUT - Consider black's bishop on g7 for a minute. How many turns does it take the g7 bishop to reach c7 if it decided to go over there? How about a5 or b6? There are a significant number of black's own pieces blocking the bishops path over there. } { [%csl Ba5,Bb6,Bc7,Gc5] } 10... Nf6 11. Bd2 { Now ask the question, does white have more pieces to aim at a5, b6, and c7 than black has to defend those squares? He does. We finally have a definition to work with: A weak square or set of squares is simply a place in the chess board where one side has the potential to attack more times than the other side can defend. } { [%csl Ba5,Bb6,Bc7] } 11... Ne4 12. Rfd1 Nxd2 { Black perhaps understands this and is trying to remove one of the offending pieces. If this move wasn't coming from a world champion, I would assume it was not a well considered move. In this case, we have to believe that black had some idea of his perceived weak squares in mind. } 13. Rxd2 Qd6 14. Rc1 { Aiming at c7. } 14... b6 15. Rdc2 { Aiming at c7. } 15... Bb7 16. Qa4! { This move attempts to stop black from trying Rac8, or Rfc8 by pressuring the a pawn. With the white rooks on the board, aiming at the weak c7, and black unable to trade them, white must be ahead in that location. } 16... a6 17. Rc7 b5 18. Qa5 { Did we see this coming? Once white occupies all the squares that black weakened, the situation for black gets dire. } 18... Rab8 19. R1c5 { We can trace this position all the way back to the moment where black played Bg7 and then allowed a symmetrical pawn structure. It was almost inevitable, assuming the white player had these weak dark squares in mind. } 19... Rfd8 { Black makes a serious error, and leaves tactics open. Rubinstein does not miss them. } 20. Ne5! { Black can not play BxN, or he will lose material. } 20... Bf6 (20... Bxe5?? 21. dxe5 Qxe5 { [%cal Ga5d8] } 22. Rxb7 { The d8 rook is hanging if black captures at b7. }) 21. Nc6! { Black can not capture the knight or he will lose his queen. } 21... e6 { I hope this study helps. The game was over just a few short moves and some seriously troubling tactics later. } (21... Bxc6?? 22. R5xc6 { The queen is trapped! }) 22. g3 { The genius of Rubinstein. He sees deeply and knows he has an extra move that he can use to fix one problematic variation with a back row mate later. I will point and shout when it comes up. } 22... Rf8 23. Nxb8 Rxb8 24. Bxb5 { Understanding this position is like playing chess on a roller coaster. It's hard. However, at least we know now how we arrived here. Weak dark squares where white took advantage by aiming more pieces at them than black had to defend them. } 24... Bd8 25. Be8 Qf8 26. Rxb7 Bxa5 27. Rxb8 Qd6 28. Rb7 Bb6 29. Rc6 Qb4 30. Bxf7+ { The variation in question: if white had not thought to play 22. g3, he could not play now RxB and win the game 8 moves later. \o/ } 1-0


